claim.claim-text:
1. A current detector utilizing the Hall-effect for detection or measurement of electric current, comprising: 
(a) a current-path conductor for carrying current to be detected or measured; 
(b) a Hall generator disposed opposite the current-path conductor for generating a Hall voltage proportional to the strength of a magnetic field due to the current flowing through the current-path conductor; 
(c) magnetic layer means disposed opposite the current-path conductor via the Hall generator; and 
(d) a casing of electrically insulating material holding the current-path conductor and the Hall generator and the magnetic layer means in prescribed relative positions.

7. A current detector utilizing the Hall-effect for detection or measurement of electric current, comprising: (A) a current-path conductor assembly comprising: (a) a current-path conductor in the form of a piece of sheet metal for carrying current to be detected or measured; and (b) a conductor holder of electrically insulating material integrally holding the current-path conductor;
(B) Hall generator assembly comprising: (a) a Hall generator for generating a Hall voltage proportional to the strength of an applied magnetic field; (b) a magnetic layer held against the Hall generator; and (c) an encapsulation of electrically insulating material integrally enveloping the Hall generator and the magnetic layer; and
(C) the current-path conductor assembly and the Hall generator assembly being combined by bonding together the conductor holder of the current-path conductor assembly and the encapsulation of the Hall generator assembly into a unitary casing for the current detector, with the Hall generator positioned closer to the current-path conductor than is the magnetic layer in order to generate the Hall voltage in response to a magnetic field due to the current flowing through the current-path conductor.

11. A current detector utilizing the Hall-effect for detection or measurement of electric current, comprising: 
(a) a current-path conductor in the form of a piece of sheet metal adapted to provide an S-shaped current path for carrying current to be detected or measured; 
(b) Hall generator means comprising a pair of Hall generators disposed opposite the current-path conductor in positions spaced along the S-shaped current path each for generating a Hall voltage proportional to the strength of a magnetic field due to the current flowing through the current-path conductor, and an output circuit for combining the Hall voltages generated by the Hall generators; 
(c) magnetic layer means disposed opposite current-path conductor via the Hall generator means; and 
(d) a casing of electrically insulating material holding the current-path conductor and the Hall generator means and the magnetic layer means in prescribed relative positions.

17. A current detector utilizing the Hall-effect for detection or measurement of electric current, comprising: 
(a) a pair of elongate current-path conductors each for carrying current to be detected or measured, the pair of current-path conductors extending in parallel spaced relationship to each other and each terminating in a pair of terminal portions at both ends thereof; 
(b) a Hall generator disposed opposite the pair of current-path conductors for generating a Hall voltage proportional to a difference between the magnitudes of currents flowing through the respective current-path conductors; 
(c) magnetic layer means disposed opposite the pair of current-path conductors via the Hall generator; and 
(d) a casing of electrically insulating material holing the pair of current-path conductors and the Hall generator and the magnetic layer means in prescribed relative positions.
